            "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
            "body": "It's a bit unintuitive at first, but the problem is that `settings.ltex.enabled` only tell *ltex* which filetypes to check, but not *nvim*. What happens here is not really a bug, you just need to tell nvim-lspconfig when to startup ltex by adding `typst` to the list of filetypes.\r\n\r\nThe `server_configurations/ltex.lua` file you manually edited basically does that, but you can do that already more simply in the `setup` call like this:\r\n\r\n```lua\r\nlocal lspconfig = require(\"lspconfig\")\r\nlspconfig.ltex.setup({\r\n  filetypes = { \"latex\", \"typst\", \"typ\", \"bib\", \"markdown\", \"plaintex\", \"tex\" }, --  <-- add this\r\n  settings = {\r\n    ltex = {\r\n      enabled = { \"latex\", \"typst\", \"typ\", \"bib\", \"markdown\", \"plaintex\", \"tex\" },\r\n    }\r\n  }\r\n})\r\n```",
